In an alternating path, the endpoints are in $J \setminus I$ and the other vertices are in $I \setminus J$. Since there are more endpoints in $J \setminus I$, by the pigeonhole principle, there must be some vertex $v \in J \setminus I$ such that the alternating path starting at $v$ has its other endpoint in $I \setminus J$ or not matched in $I$. 

If the other endpoint is matched in $I$, then we can take the path and form a new matching $M_I' = M_I \Delta P$, where $P$ is the path. This new matching will match $I \cup \{v\}$. 

So, we need to show that there exists some $x \in J \setminus I$ such that $I \cup \{x\}$ is matchable. 

